    <!-- ===== THEORY ===== -->
    <section id="theory" class="section">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header">
          <h2 class="section-title">Analog Communication Theory</h2>
          <p class="section-subtitle">Core concepts every EE student should know</p>
        </div>

        <div class="theory-grid">
          <details class="theory-card" open>
            <summary>
              <span class="theory-num">01</span>
              <span>What is an Analog Signal?</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="theory-body">
              <p>An <strong>analog signal</strong> is a continuous-time signal in which the signal value varies smoothly and can take on any value within a given range. Unlike digital signals that are discrete, analog signals represent physical quantities such as sound, light, and temperature as continuous waveforms.</p>
              <p>Mathematically, a basic analog signal can be represented as:</p>
              <div class="formula">x(t) = A · sin(2πft + φ)</div>
              <p>Where <strong>A</strong> is the amplitude, <strong>f</strong> is the frequency, and <strong>φ</strong> is the phase.</p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="theory-card">
            <summary>
              <span class="theory-num">02</span>
              <span>Time Domain Representation</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="theory-body">
              <p>The <strong>time domain</strong> representation displays how a signal's amplitude changes over time. It is the most intuitive way to visualize a waveform — the horizontal axis represents time and the vertical axis represents amplitude.</p>
              <p>Key parameters visible in the time domain:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Period (T):</strong> Time for one complete cycle, T = 1/f</li>
                <li><strong>Peak Amplitude:</strong> Maximum deviation from zero</li>
                <li><strong>Phase:</strong> Horizontal shift of the waveform</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="theory-card">
            <summary>
              <span class="theory-num">03</span>
              <span>Frequency Domain Representation</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="theory-body">
              <p>The <strong>frequency domain</strong> shows which frequencies are present in a signal and their magnitudes. The transformation from time domain to frequency domain is achieved using the <strong>Fourier Transform</strong>.</p>
              <p>The Discrete Fourier Transform (DFT) is defined as:</p>
              <div class="formula">X[k] = Σ x[n] · e<sup>-j2πkn/N</sup></div>
              <p>A pure sine wave at frequency <em>f</em> will appear as a single spike at <em>f</em> in the frequency spectrum.</p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="theory-card">
            <summary>
              <span class="theory-num">04</span>
              <span>Importance of Spectrum Analysis</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="theory-body">
              <p>Spectrum analysis is fundamental in analog communication because:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Bandwidth Allocation:</strong> Determines how much of the frequency spectrum a signal occupies, which is critical for efficient channel usage.</li>
                <li><strong>Interference Detection:</strong> Identifies unwanted frequency components from noise or neighboring channels.</li>
                <li><strong>Filter Design:</strong> Guides the design of filters to pass desired frequencies and reject others.</li>
                <li><strong>Modulation Analysis:</strong> Reveals the carrier frequency and sidebands in AM, FM, and PM modulated signals.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="theory-card">
            <summary>
              <span class="theory-num">05</span>
              <span>Applications in Analog Communication</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="theory-body">
              <p>Analog signals and spectrum analysis are used in:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>AM/FM Radio Broadcasting:</strong> Signal modulation and demodulation rely on frequency domain understanding.</li>
                <li><strong>Telephony:</strong> Voice signals are analog and their bandwidth determines channel capacity.</li>
                <li><strong>Television:</strong> Video signals are composite analog waveforms requiring spectral management.</li>
                <li><strong>Radar Systems:</strong> Pulse waveform spectrum analysis determines range resolution.</li>
                <li><strong>Biomedical Instrumentation:</strong> ECG, EEG signals are analyzed in the frequency domain for diagnostics.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="theory-card">
            <summary>
              <span class="theory-num">06</span>
              <span>Communication System Signal Analysis</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="theory-body">
              <p>In a communication system, signal analysis involves understanding how information-bearing signals interact with the transmission medium:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Signal-to-Noise Ratio (SNR):</strong> Comparing signal power to noise power in the frequency domain.</li>
                <li><strong>Channel Bandwidth:</strong> The range of frequencies a channel can support, directly related to Shannon's capacity theorem.</li>
                <li><strong>Nyquist Criterion:</strong> The minimum sampling rate must be at least 2× the highest frequency component (f<sub>s</sub> ≥ 2f<sub>max</sub>).</li>
                <li><strong>Aliasing:</strong> Occurs when the sampling frequency is below the Nyquist rate, causing spectral overlap.</li>
              </ul>
              <div class="formula">C = B · log₂(1 + SNR) — Shannon's Channel Capacity</div>
            </div>
          </details>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

